\c 13
\p
\v 1 Later that day Jesus left the house and sat down on the shore of the Lake.
\v 2 Soon a vast crowd gathered around Him, so he got into a boat and sat in it, while all the people stood on the shore.
\v 3 He used figurative stories to teach them many things, including this one:
\pi A farmer went out to sprinkle seed on his field.
\v 4 As he did that, some of the seed fell on the path that ran along the field, and the birds came and pecked it up.
\v 5 Some fell on rocky ground, where there was scanty soil among the rocks. Sprouts quickly appeared through the thin soil,
\v 6 but the heat of the sun quickly scorched them because their roots couldn't penetrate deep enough to find water.
\v 7 Some seed also fell in a patch of thorns, but the thorns choked out the tender shoots.
\v 8 But other seed fell on good soil, and it produced a good crop. Some single seeds yeilded 30 kenals, and others 60, and some even produced 100.
\pi
\v 9 Listen and think! Don't let what I say go in one ear and out the other.
\p
\v 10 Soon afterward, Jesus' disciples came and asked him, “Why is your teaching filled with so many figurative stories?”
\p
\v 11 He replied:
\pi You disciples have been given the privilege of understanding many previously unrevealed truths about God's kingdom, but not all of my andience have been given that privilege.
\v 12 To those who listen and try to understand what I teach, more and more insights will generously be revealed. But those who don't try to remember and understand, what small insights they have will be wiped from their memory.
\v 13 When many in my andience hear my figurative stories, briefly see something but end up perceiving nothing, and hear something but never unlock the meaning of what is pictured.
\v 14 So it turns out exactly like what God said when he was speaking to the prophet Isaiah:
\pi Go say to these people:
\q3 “Even though you keep on listening, you will never understand,
\q3 and though you plainly see the things the LORD is doing, you won’t get the point.”
\q3
\v 15 For these people have let their hearts become calloused.
\q3 They don't want to hear so are now almost deaf,
\q3 and since they don't want to see, they simply close their eyes.
\q3 So, off they go, with ears not hearing, eyes not seeing, and hearts not understanding.
\q3 If only they would turn around, they would find Me waiting to heal them.\x + \xo 13:15 \xt Is. 6:9-10 LXX\x*
\pi
\v 16 But God has given you a huge blessing, because he has opened your ears and eyes, enabling you to understand what you hear and perceive the meaning of what you see.
\v 17 Remember this: Many prophets and righteous people in the past have longed to see and hear the things you are hearing and seeing, but they were not given that privilege.
\pi
\v 18 %%To you then I will explain the parable of the Sower.
\v 19 When a man hears the Message concerning the Kingdom and does not understand it, the Evil one comes and catches away what has been sown in his heart. This is he who has received the seed by the road-side.
\v 20 He who has received the seed on the rocky ground is the man who hears the Message and immediately receives it with joy.
\v 21 It has struck no root, however, within him. He continues for a time, but when suffering comes, or persecution, because of the Message, he at once stumbles and falls.
\v 22 He who has received the seed among the thorns is the man who hears the Message, but the cares of the present age and the delusions of riches quite stifle the Message, and it becomes unfruitful.
\v 23 But he who has received the seed on good ground is he who hears and understands. Such hearers give a return, and yield one a hundred for one, another sixty, another thirty.”)
\p
\v 24 Another parable He put before them. “The Kingdom of the Heavens,” He said, “may be compared to a man who has sown good seed in his field,
\v 25 but during the night his enemy comes, and over the first seed he sows darnel among the wheat, and goes away.
\v 26 But when the blade shoots up and the grain is formed, then appears the darnel also.
\v 27 “So the farmer’s men come and ask him, “‘Sir, was it not good seed that you sowed on your land? Where then does the darnel come from?’
\v 28 “‘Some enemy has done this,’ he said. “‘Shall we go, and collect it?’ the men inquire.
\v 29 “‘No,’ he replied, ‘for fear that while collecting the darnel you should at the same time root up the wheat with it.
\v 30 Leave both to grow together until the harvest, and at harvest-time I will direct the reapers, Collect the darnel first, and make it up into bundles to burn it, but bring all the wheat into my barn.’”
\v 31 Another parable He put before them. “The Kingdom of the Heavens,” He said, “is like a mustard-seed, which a man takes and sows in his ground.
\v 32 It is the smallest of all seeds, and yet when full-grown it is larger than any herb and forms a tree, so that the birds come and build in its branches.”
\v 33 Another parable He spoke to them. “The Kingdom of the Heavens,” He said, “is like yeast which a woman takes and buries in a bushel of flour, for it to work there till the whole mass has risen.”
\v 34 All this Jesus spoke to the people in figurative language, and except in figurative language He spoke nothing to them,
\v 35 in fulfilment of the saying of the Prophet, “I will open my mouth in figurative language, I will utter things kept hidden since the creation of all things.”
\v 36 When He had dismissed the people and had returned to the house, His disciples came to Him with the request, “Explain to us the parable of the darnel sown in the field.”
\v 37 “The sower of the good seed,” He replied, “is the Son of Man;
\v 38 the field is the world; the good seed— these are the sons of the Kingdom; the darnel, the sons of the Evil one.
\v 39 The enemy who sows the darnel is *the Devil*; the harvest is the Close of the Age; the reapers are the angels.
\v 40 As then the darnel is collected together and burnt up with fire, so will it be at the Close of the Age.
\v 41 The Son of Man will commission His angels, and they will gather out of His Kingdom all causes of sin and all who violate His laws;
\v 42 and these they will throw into the fiery furnace. There will be the weeping aloud and the gnashing of teeth.
\v 43 Then will the righteous shine out like the sun in their Father’s Kingdom. Listen, every one who has ears!
\p
\v 44 “The Kingdom of the Heavens is like treasure buried in the open country, which a man finds, but buries again, and, in his joy about it, goes and sells all he has and buys that piece of ground.
\v 45 “Again the Kingdom of the Heavens is like a jewel merchant who is in quest of choice pearls.
\v 46 He finds one most costly pearl; he goes away; and though it costs all he has, he buys it.
\v 47 “Again the Kingdom of the Heavens is like a draw-net let down into the sea, which encloses fish of all sorts.
\v 48 When full, they haul it up on the beach, and sit down and collect the good fish in baskets, while the worthless they throw away.
\v 49 So will it be at the Close of the Age. The angels will go forth and separate the wicked from among the righteous,
\v 50 and will throw them into the fiery furnace. There will be the weeping aloud and the gnashing of teeth.”
\v 51 “Have you understood all this?” He asked. “Yes,” they said.
\v 52 “Therefore,” He said, “remember that every Scribe well trained for the Kingdom of the Heavens is like a householder who brings out of his storehouse new things and old.”
\p
\v 53 Jesus concluded this series of parables and then departed.
\v 54 And He came into His own country and proceeded to teach in their synagogue, so that they were filled with astonishment and exclaimed, “Where did he obtain such wisdom, and these wondrous powers?
\v 55 Is not this the carpenter’s son? Is not his mother called Mary? And are not his brothers, James, Joseph, Simon and Judah?
\v 56 And his sisters— are they not all living here among us? Where then did he get all this?”
\v 57 So they turned angrily away from Him. But Jesus said to them, “There is no prophet left without honour except in his own country and among his own family.”
\v 58 And He performed but few mighty deeds there because of their want of faith.
\p